  "prompt": "Nerve cell function?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, also known as neurons, are the fundamental units of the nervous system and are responsible for transmitting information throughout the body. Their primary functions include:\n\n1. **Receiving Information**:\n   - **Dendrites**: These branched extensions of the neuron receive chemical signals (neurotransmitters) from other neurons at synapses, converting them into electrical signals.\n\n2. **Integrating Information**:\n   - **Cell Body (Soma)**: The soma processes the incoming signals from dendrites. If the combined electrical signals reach a certain threshold, it triggers an action potential.\n\n3. **Transmitting Information**:\n   - **Axon**: This long, slender projection carries the electrical signal (action potential) away from the cell body toward other neurons, muscles, or glands.\n   - **Myelin Sheath**: A fatty layer that insulates the axon, speeding up the transmission of the electrical signal.\n\n4. **Transmitting Signals to Other Cells**:\n   - **Axon Terminals**: At the end of the axon, the electrical signal triggers the release of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft, a small gap between the axon terminal and the next neuron or target cell.\n   - **Synapse**: The junction where neurotransmitters are released to bind to receptors on the dendrites or cell bodies of adjacent neurons or other target cells, continuing the signal transmission.\n\n### Key Functions of Neurons:\n- **Sensory Neurons**: Carry information from sensory receptors to the central nervous system (CNS).\n- **Motor Neurons**: Transmit signals from the CNS to muscles or glands, resulting in movement or secretion.\n- **Interneurons**: Connect neurons within the CNS, integrating and processing information.\n\nNeurons work together in complex networks to enable functions such as thinking, movement, sensation, and regulation of bodily processes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
